arc_fitting.description: Enable to get a G-code file which has G2 and G3 moves. G-code resolution will be used as the fitting tolerance.
arc_fitting.label: Arc fitting

autoemit_temperature_commands.description:
When enabled, PrusaSlicer will check whether your Custom Start G-Code contains M104 or M190. If so, the temperatures will not be emitted automatically so you're free to customize the order of heating commands and other custom actions. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all PrusaSlicer settings, so you can put a "M109 S[first_layer_temperature]" command wherever you want.
If your Custom Start G-Code does NOT contain M104 or M190, PrusaSlicer will execute the Start G-Code after bed reached its target temperature and extruder just started heating.

When disabled, PrusaSlicer will NOT emit commands to heat up extruder and bed, leaving both to Custom Start G-Code.
autoemit_temperature_commands.label: Emit temperature commands automatically

avoid_crossing_curled_overhangs.description: Plan travel moves such that the extruder avoids areas where the filament may be curled up. This is mostly happening on steeper rounded overhangs and may cause a crash with the nozzle. This feature slows down both the print and the G-code generation.
avoid_crossing_curled_overhangs.label: Avoid crossing curled overhangs (Experimental)

avoid_crossing_perimeters.description: Optimize travel moves in order to minimize the crossing of perimeters. This is mostly useful with Bowden extruders which suffer from oozing. This feature slows down both the print and the G-code generation.
avoid_crossing_perimeters.label: Avoid crossing perimeters

avoid_crossing_perimeters_max_detour.description: The maximum detour length for avoid crossing perimeters. If the detour is longer than this value, avoid crossing perimeters is not applied for this travel path. Detour length could be specified either as an absolute value or as percentage (for example 50%) of a direct travel path.
avoid_crossing_perimeters_max_detour.label: Avoid crossing perimeters - Max detour length

bed_temperature.description: Bed temperature for layers after the first one. Set this to zero to disable bed temperature control commands in the output.
bed_temperature.label: Other layers

before_layer_gcode.description: This custom code is inserted at every layer change, right before the Z move. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all Slic3r settings as well as [layer_num] and [layer_z].
before_layer_gcode.label: Before layer change G-code

between_objects_gcode.description: This code is inserted between objects when using sequential printing. By default extruder and bed temperature are reset using non-wait command; however if M104, M109, M140 or M190 are detected in this custom code, Slic3r will not add temperature commands. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all Slic3r settings, so you can put a "M109 S[first_layer_temperature]" command wherever you want.
between_objects_gcode.label: Between objects G-code

binary_gcode.description: Enable, if the firmware supports binary G-code format (bgcode). To generate .bgcode files, make sure you have binary G-code enabled in Configuration->Preferences->Other.
binary_gcode.label: Supports binary G-code

bottom_fill_pattern.description: Fill pattern for bottom infill. This only affects the bottom external visible layer, and not its adjacent solid shells.
bottom_fill_pattern.label: Bottom fill pattern

bottom_solid_layers.description: Number of solid layers to generate on bottom surfaces.
bottom_solid_layers.label: Bottom

bottom_solid_min_thickness.description: The number of bottom solid layers is increased above bottom_solid_layers if necessary to satisfy minimum thickness of bottom shell.
bottom_solid_min_thickness.label: Bottom

bridge_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for bridges. Set zero to disable acceleration control for bridges.
bridge_acceleration.label: Bridge

bridge_angle.description: Bridging angle override. If left to zero, the bridging angle will be calculated automatically. Otherwise the provided angle will be used for all bridges. Use 180o for zero angle.
bridge_angle.label: Bridging angle

bridge_fan_speed.description: This fan speed is enforced during all bridges and overhangs.
bridge_fan_speed.label: Bridges fan speed

bridge_flow_ratio.description: This factor affects the amount of plastic for bridging. You can decrease it slightly to pull the extrudates and prevent sagging, although default settings are usually good and you should experiment with cooling (use a fan) before tweaking this.
bridge_flow_ratio.label: Bridge flow ratio

brim_separation.description: Offset of brim from the printed object. The offset is applied after the elephant foot compensation.
brim_separation.label: Brim separation gap

brim_type.description: The places where the brim will be printed around each object on the first layer.
brim_type.label: Brim type

brim_width.description: The horizontal width of the brim that will be printed around each object on the first layer. When raft is used, no brim is generated (use raft_first_layer_expansion).
brim_width.label: Brim width

color_change_gcode.description: This G-code will be used as a code for the color change
color_change_gcode.label: Color change G-code

colorprint_heights.description: Heights at which a filament change is to occur.
colorprint_heights.label: Colorprint height

compatible_printers_condition.description: A boolean expression using the configuration values of an active printer profile. If this expression evaluates to true, this profile is considered compatible with the active printer profile.
compatible_printers_condition.label: Compatible printers condition

compatible_prints_condition.description: A boolean expression using the configuration values of an active print profile. If this expression evaluates to true, this profile is considered compatible with the active print profile.
compatible_prints_condition.label: Compatible print profiles condition

complete_objects.description: When printing multiple objects or copies, this feature will complete each object before moving onto next one (and starting it from its bottom layer). This feature is useful to avoid the risk of ruined prints. Slic3r should warn and prevent you from extruder collisions, but beware.
complete_objects.label: Complete individual objects

cooling.description: This flag enables the automatic cooling logic that adjusts print speed and fan speed according to layer printing time.
cooling.label: Enable auto cooling

cooling_tube_length.description: Length of the cooling tube to limit space for cooling moves inside it.
cooling_tube_length.label: Cooling tube length

cooling_tube_retraction.description: Distance of the center-point of the cooling tube from the extruder tip.
cooling_tube_retraction.label: Cooling tube position

default_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will be reset to after the role-specific acceleration values are used (perimeter/infill). Set zero to prevent resetting acceleration at all.
default_acceleration.label: Default

default_filament_profile.description: Default filament profile associated with the current printer profile. On selection of the current printer profile, this filament profile will be activated.
default_filament_profile.label: Default filament profile

default_print_profile.description: Default print profile associated with the current printer profile. On selection of the current printer profile, this print profile will be activated.
default_print_profile.label: Default print profile

deretract_speed.description: The speed for loading of a filament into extruder after retraction (it only applies to the extruder motor). If left to zero, the retraction speed is used.
deretract_speed.label: Deretraction Speed

disable_fan_first_layers.description: You can set this to a positive value to disable fan at all during the first layers, so that it does not make adhesion worse.
disable_fan_first_layers.label: Disable fan for the first

dont_support_bridges.description: Experimental option for preventing support material from being generated under bridged areas.
dont_support_bridges.label: Don't support bridges

draft_shield.description:
With draft shield active, the skirt will be printed skirt_distance from the object, possibly intersecting brim.
Enabled = skirt is as tall as the highest printed object.
Limited = skirt is as tall as specified by skirt_height.
This is useful to protect an ABS or ASA print from warping and detaching from print bed due to wind draft.
draft_shield.label: Draft shield

duplicate_distance.description: Distance used for the auto-arrange feature of the plater.
duplicate_distance.label: Distance between copies

elefant_foot_compensation.description: The first layer will be shrunk in the XY plane by the configured value to compensate for the 1st layer squish aka an Elephant Foot effect.
elefant_foot_compensation.label: Elephant foot compensation

enable_dynamic_fan_speeds.description: This setting enables dynamic fan speed control on overhangs.
enable_dynamic_fan_speeds.label: Enable dynamic fan speeds

enable_dynamic_overhang_speeds.description: This setting enables dynamic speed control on overhangs.
enable_dynamic_overhang_speeds.label: Enable dynamic overhang speeds

end_filament_gcode.default_value: "; Filament-specific end gcode \n;END gcode for filament\n"
end_filament_gcode.description: This end procedure is inserted at the end of the output file, before the printer end gcode (and before any toolchange from this filament in case of multimaterial printers). Note that you can use placeholder variables for all PrusaSlicer settings. If you have multiple extruders, the gcode is processed in extruder order.
end_filament_gcode.label: End G-code

end_gcode.default_value:
M104 S0 ; turn off temperature
G28 X0  ; home X axis
M84     ; disable motors
end_gcode.description: This end procedure is inserted at the end of the output file. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all PrusaSlicer settings.
end_gcode.label: End G-code

external_perimeter_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for external perimeters. Set zero to use the value for perimeters.
external_perimeter_acceleration.label: External perimeters

external_perimeter_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for external perimeters. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise 1.125 x nozzle diameter will be used. If expressed as percentage (for example 200%), it will be computed over layer height.
external_perimeter_extrusion_width.label: External perimeters

external_perimeter_speed.description: This separate setting will affect the speed of external perimeters (the visible ones). If expressed as percentage (for example: 80%) it will be calculated on the perimeters speed setting above. Set to zero for auto.
external_perimeter_speed.label: External perimeters

external_perimeters_first.description: Print contour perimeters from the outermost one to the innermost one instead of the default inverse order.
external_perimeters_first.label: External perimeters first

extra_loading_move.description: When set to zero, the distance the filament is moved from parking position during load is exactly the same as it was moved back during unload. When positive, it is loaded further,  if negative, the loading move is shorter than unloading.
extra_loading_move.label: Extra loading distance

extra_perimeters.description: Add more perimeters when needed for avoiding gaps in sloping walls. Slic3r keeps adding perimeters, until more than 70% of the loop immediately above is supported.
extra_perimeters.label: Extra perimeters if needed

extra_perimeters_on_overhangs.description: Detect overhang areas where bridges cannot be anchored, and fill them with extra perimeter paths. These paths are anchored to the nearby non-overhang area when possible.
extra_perimeters_on_overhangs.label: Extra perimeters on overhangs (Experimental)

extruder.description: The extruder to use (unless more specific extruder settings are specified). This value overrides perimeter and infill extruders, but not the support extruders.
extruder.label: Extruder

extruder_clearance_height.description: Set this to the vertical distance between your nozzle tip and (usually) the X carriage rods. In other words, this is the height of the clearance cylinder around your extruder, and it represents the maximum depth the extruder can peek before colliding with other printed objects.
extruder_clearance_height.label: Height

extruder_clearance_radius.description: Set this to the clearance radius around your extruder. If the extruder is not centered, choose the largest value for safety. This setting is used to check for collisions and to display the graphical preview in the plater.
extruder_clearance_radius.label: Radius

extruder_colour.description: This is only used in the Slic3r interface as a visual help.
extruder_colour.label: Extruder Color

extruder_offset.description: If your firmware doesn't handle the extruder displacement you need the G-code to take it into account. This option lets you specify the displacement of each extruder with respect to the first one. It expects positive coordinates (they will be subtracted from the XY coordinate).
extruder_offset.label: Extruder offset

extrusion_axis.description: Use this option to set the axis letter associated to your printer's extruder (usually E but some printers use A).
extrusion_axis.label: Extrusion axis

extrusion_multiplier.description: This factor changes the amount of flow proportionally. You may need to tweak this setting to get nice surface finish and correct single wall widths. Usual values are between 0.9 and 1.1. If you think you need to change this more, check filament diameter and your firmware E steps.
extrusion_multiplier.label: Extrusion multiplier

extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to allow a manual extrusion width. If left to zero, Slic3r derives extrusion widths from the nozzle diameter (see the tooltips for perimeter extrusion width, infill extrusion width etc). If expressed as percentage (for example: 230%), it will be computed over layer height.
extrusion_width.label: Default extrusion width

fan_always_on.description: If this is enabled, fan will never be disabled and will be kept running at least at its minimum speed. Useful for PLA, harmful for ABS.
fan_always_on.label: Keep fan always on

fan_below_layer_time.description: If layer print time is estimated below this number of seconds, fan will be enabled and its speed will be calculated by interpolating the minimum and maximum speeds.
fan_below_layer_time.label: Enable fan if layer print time is below

filament_colour.description: This is only used in the Slic3r interface as a visual help.
filament_colour.label: Color

filament_cooling_final_speed.description: Cooling moves are gradually accelerating towards this speed.
filament_cooling_final_speed.label: Speed of the last cooling move

filament_cooling_initial_speed.description: Cooling moves are gradually accelerating beginning at this speed.
filament_cooling_initial_speed.label: Speed of the first cooling move

filament_cooling_moves.description: Filament is cooled by being moved back and forth in the cooling tubes. Specify desired number of these moves.
filament_cooling_moves.label: Number of cooling moves

filament_cost.description: Enter your filament cost per kg here. This is only for statistical information.
filament_cost.label: Cost

filament_density.description: Enter your filament density here. This is only for statistical information. A decent way is to weigh a known length of filament and compute the ratio of the length to volume. Better is to calculate the volume directly through displacement.
filament_density.label: Density

filament_deretract_speed.description: The speed for loading of a filament into extruder after retraction (it only applies to the extruder motor). If left to zero, the retraction speed is used.
filament_deretract_speed.label: Deretraction Speed

filament_diameter.description: Enter your filament diameter here. Good precision is required, so use a caliper and do multiple measurements along the filament, then compute the average.
filament_diameter.label: Diameter

filament_load_time.description: Time for the printer firmware (or the Multi Material Unit 2.0) to load a new filament during a tool change (when executing the T code). This time is added to the total print time by the G-code time estimator.
filament_load_time.label: Filament load time

filament_loading_speed.description: Speed used for loading the filament on the wipe tower.
filament_loading_speed.label: Loading speed

filament_loading_speed_start.description: Speed used at the very beginning of loading phase.
filament_loading_speed_start.label: Loading speed at the start

filament_max_volumetric_speed.description: Maximum volumetric speed allowed for this filament. Limits the maximum volumetric speed of a print to the minimum of print and filament volumetric speed. Set to zero for no limit.
filament_max_volumetric_speed.label: Max volumetric speed

filament_minimal_purge_on_wipe_tower.description: After a tool change, the exact position of the newly loaded filament inside the nozzle may not be known, and the filament pressure is likely not yet stable. Before purging the print head into an infill or a sacrificial object, Slic3r will always prime this amount of material into the wipe tower to produce successive infill or sacrificial object extrusions reliably.
filament_minimal_purge_on_wipe_tower.label: Minimal purge on wipe tower

filament_multitool_ramming.description: Perform ramming when using multitool printer (i.e. when the 'Single Extruder Multimaterial' in Printer Settings is unchecked). When checked, a small amount of filament is rapidly extruded on the wipe tower just before the toolchange. This option is only used when the wipe tower is enabled.
filament_multitool_ramming.label: Enable ramming for multitool setups

filament_multitool_ramming_flow.description: Flow used for ramming the filament before the toolchange.
filament_multitool_ramming_flow.label: Multitool ramming flow

filament_multitool_ramming_volume.description: The volume to be rammed before the toolchange.
filament_multitool_ramming_volume.label: Multitool ramming volume

filament_notes.description: You can put your notes regarding the filament here.
filament_notes.label: Filament notes

filament_ramming_parameters.description: This string is edited by RammingDialog and contains ramming specific parameters.
filament_ramming_parameters.label: Ramming parameters

filament_retract_before_travel.description: Retraction is not triggered when travel moves are shorter than this length.
filament_retract_before_travel.label: Minimum travel after retraction

filament_retract_before_wipe.description: With bowden extruders, it may be wise to do some amount of quick retract before doing the wipe movement.
filament_retract_before_wipe.label: Retract amount before wipe

filament_retract_layer_change.description: This flag enforces a retraction whenever a Z move is done.
filament_retract_layer_change.label: Retract on layer change

filament_retract_length.description: When retraction is triggered, filament is pulled back by the specified amount (the length is measured on raw filament, before it enters the extruder).
filament_retract_length.label: Retraction length

filament_retract_length_toolchange.description: When retraction is triggered before changing tool, filament is pulled back by the specified amount (the length is measured on raw filament, before it enters the extruder).
filament_retract_length_toolchange.label: Length

filament_retract_lift_above.description: If you set this to a positive value, Z lift will only take place above the specified absolute Z. You can tune this setting for skipping lift on the first layers.
filament_retract_lift_above.label: Above Z

filament_retract_lift_below.description: If you set this to a positive value, Z lift will only take place below the specified absolute Z. You can tune this setting for limiting lift to the first layers.
filament_retract_lift_below.label: Below Z

filament_retract_restart_extra.description: When the retraction is compensated after the travel move, the extruder will push this additional amount of filament. This setting is rarely needed.
filament_retract_restart_extra.label: Deretraction extra length

filament_retract_restart_extra_toolchang.description: When the retraction is compensated after changing tool, the extruder will push this additional amount of filament.
filament_retract_restart_extra_toolchang.label: Extra length on restart

filament_retract_speed.description: The speed for retractions (it only applies to the extruder motor).
filament_retract_speed.label: Retraction Speed

filament_soluble.description: Soluble material is most likely used for a soluble support.
filament_soluble.label: Soluble material

filament_spool_weight.description: Enter weight of the empty filament spool. One may weigh a partially consumed filament spool before printing and one may compare the measured weight with the calculated weight of the filament with the spool to find out whether the amount of filament on the spool is sufficient to finish the print.
filament_spool_weight.label: Spool weight

filament_toolchange_delay.description: Time to wait after the filament is unloaded. May help to get reliable toolchanges with flexible materials that may need more time to shrink to original dimensions.
filament_toolchange_delay.label: Delay after unloading

filament_travel_lift_before_obstacle.description: If enabled, PrusaSlicer detects obstacles along the travel path and makes the slope steeper in case an obstacle might be hit during the initial phase of the travel.
filament_travel_lift_before_obstacle.label: Steeper ramp before obstacles

filament_travel_max_lift.description: Maximum lift height of the ramping lift. It may not be reached if the next position is close to the old one.
filament_travel_max_lift.label: Maximum ramping lift

filament_travel_ramping_lift.description: Generates a ramping lift instead of lifting the extruder directly upwards. The travel is split into two phases: the ramp and the standard horizontal travel. This option helps reduce stringing.
filament_travel_ramping_lift.label: Use ramping lift

filament_travel_slope.description: Slope of the ramp in the initial phase of the travel.
filament_travel_slope.label: Ramping slope angle

filament_type.description: The filament material type for use in custom G-codes.
filament_type.label: Filament type

filament_unload_time.description: Time for the printer firmware (or the Multi Material Unit 2.0) to unload a filament during a tool change (when executing the T code). This time is added to the total print time by the G-code time estimator.
filament_unload_time.label: Filament unload time

filament_unloading_speed.description: Speed used for unloading the filament on the wipe tower (does not affect  initial part of unloading just after ramming).
filament_unloading_speed.label: Unloading speed

filament_unloading_speed_start.description: Speed used for unloading the tip of the filament immediately after ramming.
filament_unloading_speed_start.label: Unloading speed at the start

filament_wipe.description: This flag will move the nozzle while retracting to minimize the possible blob on leaky extruders.
filament_wipe.label: Wipe while retracting

fill_angle.description: Default base angle for infill orientation. Cross-hatching will be applied to this. Bridges will be infilled using the best direction Slic3r can detect, so this setting does not affect them.
fill_angle.label: Fill angle

fill_density.description: Density of internal infill, expressed in the range 0% - 100%.
fill_density.label: Fill density

fill_pattern.description: Fill pattern for general low-density infill.
fill_pattern.label: Fill pattern

first_layer_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for first layer. Set zero to disable acceleration control for first layer.
first_layer_acceleration.label: First layer

first_layer_acceleration_over_raft.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for first layer of object above raft interface. Set zero to disable acceleration control for first layer of object above raft interface.
first_layer_acceleration_over_raft.label: First object layer over raft interface

first_layer_bed_temperature.description: Heated build plate temperature for the first layer. Set this to zero to disable bed temperature control commands in the output.
first_layer_bed_temperature.label: First layer

first_layer_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for first layer. You can use this to force fatter extrudates for better adhesion. If expressed as percentage (for example 120%) it will be computed over first layer height. If set to zero, it will use the default extrusion width.
first_layer_extrusion_width.label: First layer

first_layer_height.description: When printing with very low layer heights, you might still want to print a thicker bottom layer to improve adhesion and tolerance for non perfect build plates.
first_layer_height.label: First layer height

first_layer_speed.description: If expressed as absolute value in mm/s, this speed will be applied to all the print moves of the first layer, regardless of their type. If expressed as a percentage (for example: 40%) it will scale the default speeds.
first_layer_speed.label: First layer speed

first_layer_speed_over_raft.description: If expressed as absolute value in mm/s, this speed will be applied to all the print moves of the first object layer above raft interface, regardless of their type. If expressed as a percentage (for example: 40%) it will scale the default speeds.
first_layer_speed_over_raft.label: Speed of object first layer over raft interface

first_layer_temperature.description: Nozzle temperature for the first layer. If you want to control temperature manually during print, set this to zero to disable temperature control commands in the output G-code.
first_layer_temperature.label: First layer

full_fan_speed_layer.description: Fan speed will be ramped up linearly from zero at layer "disable_fan_first_layers" to maximum at layer "full_fan_speed_layer". "full_fan_speed_layer" will be ignored if lower than "disable_fan_first_layers", in which case the fan will be running at maximum allowed speed at layer "disable_fan_first_layers" + 1.
full_fan_speed_layer.label: Full fan speed at layer

fuzzy_skin_point_dist.description: Perimeters will be split into multiple segments by inserting Fuzzy skin points. Lowering the Fuzzy skin point distance will increase the number of randomly offset points on the perimeter wall.
fuzzy_skin_point_dist.label: Fuzzy skin point distance

fuzzy_skin_thickness.description: The maximum distance that each skin point can be offset (both ways), measured perpendicular to the perimeter wall.
fuzzy_skin_thickness.label: Fuzzy skin thickness

gap_fill_enabled.description: Enables filling of gaps between perimeters and between the inner most perimeters and infill.
gap_fill_enabled.label: Fill gaps

gap_fill_speed.description: Speed for filling small gaps using short zigzag moves. Keep this reasonably low to avoid too much shaking and resonance issues. Set zero to disable gaps filling.
gap_fill_speed.label: Gap fill

gcode_comments.description: Enable this to get a commented G-code file, with each line explained by a descriptive text. If you print from SD card, the additional weight of the file could make your firmware slow down.
gcode_comments.label: Verbose G-code

gcode_flavor.description: Some G/M-code commands, including temperature control and others, are not universal. Set this option to your printer's firmware to get a compatible output. The "No extrusion" flavor prevents PrusaSlicer from exporting any extrusion value at all.
gcode_flavor.label: G-code flavor

gcode_label_objects.description:
Selects whether labels should be exported at object boundaries and in what format.
OctoPrint = comments to be consumed by OctoPrint CancelObject plugin.
Firmware = firmware specific G-code (it will be chosen based on firmware flavor and it can end up to be empty).

This settings is NOT compatible with Single Extruder Multi Material setup and Wipe into Object / Wipe into Infill.
gcode_label_objects.label: Label objects

gcode_resolution.description: Maximum deviation of exported G-code paths from their full resolution counterparts. Very high resolution G-code requires huge amount of RAM to slice and preview, also a 3D printer may stutter not being able to process a high resolution G-code in a timely manner. On the other hand, a low resolution G-code will produce a low poly effect and because the G-code reduction is performed at each layer independently, visible artifacts may be produced.
gcode_resolution.label: G-code resolution

gcode_substitutions.description: Find / replace patterns in G-code lines and substitute them.
gcode_substitutions.label: G-code substitutions

high_current_on_filament_swap.description: It may be beneficial to increase the extruder motor current during the filament exchange sequence to allow for rapid ramming feed rates and to overcome resistance when loading a filament with an ugly shaped tip.
high_current_on_filament_swap.label: High extruder current on filament swap

host_type.description: Slic3r can upload G-code files to a printer host. This field must contain the kind of the host.
host_type.label: Host Type

infill_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for infill. Set zero to disable acceleration control for infill.
infill_acceleration.label: Infill

infill_anchor.description: Connect an infill line to an internal perimeter with a short segment of an additional perimeter. If expressed as percentage (example: 15%) it is calculated over infill extrusion width. PrusaSlicer tries to connect two close infill lines to a short perimeter segment. If no such perimeter segment shorter than infill_anchor_max is found, the infill line is connected to a perimeter segment at just one side and the length of the perimeter segment taken is limited to this parameter, but no longer than anchor_length_max. Set this parameter to zero to disable anchoring perimeters connected to a single infill line.
infill_anchor.label: Length of the infill anchor

infill_anchor_max.description: Connect an infill line to an internal perimeter with a short segment of an additional perimeter. If expressed as percentage (example: 15%) it is calculated over infill extrusion width. PrusaSlicer tries to connect two close infill lines to a short perimeter segment. If no such perimeter segment shorter than this parameter is found, the infill line is connected to a perimeter segment at just one side and the length of the perimeter segment taken is limited to infill_anchor, but no longer than this parameter. Set this parameter to zero to disable anchoring.
infill_anchor_max.label: Maximum length of the infill anchor

infill_every_layers.description: This feature allows to combine infill and speed up your print by extruding thicker infill layers while preserving thin perimeters, thus accuracy.
infill_every_layers.label: Combine infill every

infill_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing infill.
infill_extruder.label: Infill extruder

infill_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for infill. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise 1.125 x nozzle diameter will be used. You may want to use fatter extrudates to speed up the infill and make your parts stronger. If expressed as percentage (for example 90%) it will be computed over layer height.
infill_extrusion_width.label: Infill

infill_first.description: This option will switch the print order of perimeters and infill, making the latter first.
infill_first.label: Infill before perimeters

infill_overlap.description: This setting applies an additional overlap between infill and perimeters for better bonding. Theoretically this shouldn't be needed, but backlash might cause gaps. If expressed as percentage (example: 15%) it is calculated over perimeter extrusion width.
infill_overlap.label: Infill/perimeters overlap

infill_speed.description: Speed for printing the internal fill. Set to zero for auto.
infill_speed.label: Infill

inherits.description: Name of the profile, from which this profile inherits.
inherits.label: Inherits profile

interface_shells.description: Force the generation of solid shells between adjacent materials/volumes. Useful for multi-extruder prints with translucent materials or manual soluble support material.
interface_shells.label: Interface shells

ironing.description: Enable ironing of the top layers with the hot print head for smooth surface
ironing.label: Enable ironing

ironing_flowrate.description: Percent of a flow rate relative to object's normal layer height.
ironing_flowrate.label: Flow rate

layer_gcode.description: This custom code is inserted at every layer change, right after the Z move and before the extruder moves to the first layer point. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all Slic3r settings as well as [layer_num] and [layer_z].
layer_gcode.label: After layer change G-code

layer_height.description: This setting controls the height (and thus the total number) of the slices/layers. Thinner layers give better accuracy but take more time to print.
layer_height.label: Layer height

machine_limits_usage.description: How to apply the Machine Limits
machine_limits_usage.label: How to apply limits

machine_max_acceleration_e.description: Maximum acceleration of the E axis

machine_max_acceleration_retracting.description:
Maximum acceleration when retracting.

Not used for RepRapFirmware, which does not support it.

machine_max_acceleration_x.description: Maximum acceleration of the X axis

machine_max_acceleration_y.description: Maximum acceleration of the Y axis

machine_max_acceleration_z.description: Maximum acceleration of the Z axis

machine_max_feedrate_e.description: Maximum feedrate of the E axis

machine_max_feedrate_x.description: Maximum feedrate of the X axis

machine_max_feedrate_y.description: Maximum feedrate of the Y axis

machine_max_feedrate_z.description: Maximum feedrate of the Z axis

machine_max_jerk_e.description: Maximum jerk of the E axis

machine_max_jerk_x.description: Maximum jerk of the X axis

machine_max_jerk_y.description: Maximum jerk of the Y axis

machine_max_jerk_z.description: Maximum jerk of the Z axis

max_fan_speed.description: This setting represents the maximum speed of your fan.
max_fan_speed.label: Max

max_layer_height.description: This is the highest printable layer height for this extruder, used to cap the variable layer height and support layer height. Maximum recommended layer height is 75% of the extrusion width to achieve reasonable inter-layer adhesion. If set to 0, layer height is limited to 75% of the nozzle diameter.
max_layer_height.label: Max

max_print_height.description: Set this to the maximum height that can be reached by your extruder while printing.
max_print_height.label: Max print height

max_print_speed.description: When setting other speed settings to 0 Slic3r will autocalculate the optimal speed in order to keep constant extruder pressure. This experimental setting is used to set the highest print speed you want to allow.
max_print_speed.label: Max print speed

max_volumetric_extrusion_rate_slope_nega.description: This experimental setting is used to limit the speed of change in extrusion rate for a transition from higher speed to lower speed. A value of 1.8 mm³/s2 ensures, that a change from the extrusion rate of 5.4 mm³/s (0.45 mm extrusion width, 0.2 mm extrusion height, feedrate 60 mm/s) to 1.8 mm³/s (feedrate 20 mm/s) will take at least 2 seconds.
max_volumetric_extrusion_rate_slope_nega.label: Max volumetric slope negative

max_volumetric_extrusion_rate_slope_posi.description: This experimental setting is used to limit the speed of change in extrusion rate for a transition from lower speed to higher speed. A value of 1.8 mm³/s2 ensures, that a change from the extrusion rate of 1.8 mm³/s (0.45 mm extrusion width, 0.2 mm extrusion height, feedrate 20 mm/s) to 5.4 mm³/s (feedrate 60 mm/s) will take at least 2 seconds.
max_volumetric_extrusion_rate_slope_posi.label: Max volumetric slope positive

max_volumetric_speed.description: This experimental setting is used to set the maximum volumetric speed your extruder supports.
max_volumetric_speed.label: Max volumetric speed

min_bead_width.description: Width of the perimeter that will replace thin features (according to the Minimum feature size) of the model. If the Minimum perimeter width is thinner than the thickness of the feature, the perimeter will become as thick as the feature itself. If expressed as a percentage (for example 85%), it will be computed based on the nozzle diameter.
min_bead_width.label: Minimum perimeter width

min_fan_speed.description: This setting represents the minimum PWM your fan needs to work.
min_fan_speed.label: Min

min_feature_size.description: Minimum thickness of thin features. Model features that are thinner than this value will not be printed, while features thicker than the Minimum feature size will be widened to the Minimum perimeter width. If expressed as a percentage (for example 25%), it will be computed based on the nozzle diameter.
min_feature_size.label: Minimum feature size

min_layer_height.description: This is the lowest printable layer height for this extruder and limits the resolution for variable layer height. Typical values are between 0.05 mm and 0.1 mm.
min_layer_height.label: Min

min_print_speed.description: Slic3r will not scale speed down below this speed.
min_print_speed.label: Min print speed

min_skirt_length.description: Generate no less than the number of skirt loops required to consume the specified amount of filament on the bottom layer. For multi-extruder machines, this minimum applies to each extruder.
min_skirt_length.label: Minimal filament extrusion length

mmu_segmented_region_interlocking_depth.description: Interlocking depth of a segmented region. It will be ignored if "mmu_segmented_region_max_width" is zero or if "mmu_segmented_region_interlocking_depth"is bigger then "mmu_segmented_region_max_width". Zero disables this feature.
mmu_segmented_region_interlocking_depth.label: Interlocking depth of a segmented region

mmu_segmented_region_max_width.description: Maximum width of a segmented region. Zero disables this feature.
mmu_segmented_region_max_width.label: Maximum width of a segmented region

notes.description: You can put here your personal notes. This text will be added to the G-code header comments.
notes.label: Configuration notes

nozzle_diameter.description: This is the diameter of your extruder nozzle (for example: 0.5, 0.35 etc.)
nozzle_diameter.label: Nozzle diameter

only_retract_when_crossing_perimeters.description: Disables retraction when the travel path does not exceed the upper layer's perimeters (and thus any ooze will be probably invisible).
only_retract_when_crossing_perimeters.label: Only retract when crossing perimeters

ooze_prevention.description: This option will drop the temperature of the inactive extruders to prevent oozing.
ooze_prevention.label: Enable

output_filename_format.description: You can use all configuration options as variables inside this template. For example: [layer_height], [fill_density] etc. You can also use [timestamp], [year], [month], [day], [hour], [minute], [second], [version], [input_filename_base], [default_output_extension].
output_filename_format.label: Output filename format

overhang_fan_speed_0.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Fan speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation.
overhang_fan_speed_0.label: speed for 0% overlap (bridge)

overhang_fan_speed_1.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Fan speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation.
overhang_fan_speed_1.label: speed for 25% overlap

overhang_fan_speed_2.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Fan speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation.
overhang_fan_speed_2.label: speed for 50% overlap

overhang_fan_speed_3.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Fan speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation.
overhang_fan_speed_3.label: speed for 75% overlap

overhang_speed_0.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation. If set as percentage, the speed is calculated over the external perimeter speed.
overhang_speed_0.label: speed for 0% overlap (bridge)

overhang_speed_1.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation. If set as percentage, the speed is calculated over the external perimeter speed.
overhang_speed_1.label: speed for 25% overlap

overhang_speed_2.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation. If set as percentage, the speed is calculated over the external perimeter speed.
overhang_speed_2.label: speed for 50% overlap

overhang_speed_3.description: Overhang size is expressed as a percentage of overlap of the extrusion with the previous layer: 100% would be full overlap (no overhang), while 0% represents full overhang (floating extrusion, bridge). Speeds for overhang sizes in between are calculated via linear interpolation. If set as percentage, the speed is calculated over the external perimeter speed.
overhang_speed_3.label: speed for 75% overlap

overhangs.description: Experimental option to adjust flow for overhangs (bridge flow will be used), to apply bridge speed to them and enable fan.
overhangs.label: Detect bridging perimeters

parking_pos_retraction.description: Distance of the extruder tip from the position where the filament is parked when unloaded. This should match the value in printer firmware.
parking_pos_retraction.label: Filament parking position

pause_print_gcode.description: This G-code will be used as a code for the pause print
pause_print_gcode.label: Pause Print G-code

perimeter_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for perimeters. Set zero to disable acceleration control for perimeters.
perimeter_acceleration.label: Perimeters

perimeter_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing perimeters and brim. First extruder is 1.
perimeter_extruder.label: Perimeter extruder

perimeter_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for perimeters. You may want to use thinner extrudates to get more accurate surfaces. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise 1.125 x nozzle diameter will be used. If expressed as percentage (for example 200%) it will be computed over layer height.
perimeter_extrusion_width.label: Perimeters

perimeter_generator.description: Classic perimeter generator produces perimeters with constant extrusion width and for very thin areas is used gap-fill. Arachne engine produces perimeters with variable extrusion width. This setting also affects the Concentric infill.
perimeter_generator.label: Perimeter generator

perimeter_speed.description: Speed for perimeters (contours, aka vertical shells). Set to zero for auto.
perimeter_speed.label: Perimeters

perimeters.description: This option sets the number of perimeters to generate for each layer. Note that Slic3r may increase this number automatically when it detects sloping surfaces which benefit from a higher number of perimeters if the Extra Perimeters option is enabled.
perimeters.label: Perimeters

post_process.description: If you want to process the output G-code through custom scripts, just list their absolute paths here. Separate multiple scripts with a semicolon. Scripts will be passed the absolute path to the G-code file as the first argument, and they can access the Slic3r config settings by reading environment variables.
post_process.label: Post-processing scripts

preset_names.description: Names of presets related to the physical printer
preset_names.label: Printer preset names

print_host.description: Slic3r can upload G-code files to a printer host. This field should contain the hostname, IP address or URL of the printer host instance. Print host behind HAProxy with basic auth enabled can be accessed by putting the user name and password into the URL in the following format: https://username:password@your-octopi-address/
print_host.label: Hostname, IP or URL

printer_notes.description: You can put your notes regarding the printer here.
printer_notes.label: Printer notes

printer_variant.description: Name of the printer variant. For example, the printer variants may be differentiated by a nozzle diameter.
printer_variant.label: Printer variant

printhost_apikey.description: Slic3r can upload G-code files to a printer host. This field should contain the API Key or the password required for authentication.
printhost_apikey.label: API Key / Password

printhost_cafile.description: Custom CA certificate file can be specified for HTTPS OctoPrint connections, in crt/pem format. If left blank, the default OS CA certificate repository is used.
printhost_cafile.label: HTTPS CA File

printhost_ssl_ignore_revoke.description: Ignore HTTPS certificate revocation checks in case of missing or offline distribution points. One may want to enable this option for self signed certificates if connection fails.
printhost_ssl_ignore_revoke.label: Ignore HTTPS certificate revocation checks

raft_contact_distance.description: The vertical distance between object and raft. Ignored for soluble interface.
raft_contact_distance.label: Raft contact Z distance

raft_expansion.description: Expansion of the raft in XY plane for better stability.
raft_expansion.label: Raft expansion

raft_first_layer_density.description: Density of the first raft or support layer.
raft_first_layer_density.label: First layer density

raft_first_layer_expansion.description: Expansion of the first raft or support layer to improve adhesion to print bed.
raft_first_layer_expansion.label: First layer expansion

raft_layers.description: The object will be raised by this number of layers, and support material will be generated under it.
raft_layers.label: Raft layers

remaining_times.description: Emit M73 P[percent printed] R[remaining time in minutes] at 1 minute intervals into the G-code to let the firmware show accurate remaining time. As of now only the Prusa i3 MK3 firmware recognizes M73. Also the i3 MK3 firmware supports M73 Qxx Sxx for the silent mode.
remaining_times.label: Supports remaining times

resolution.description: Minimum detail resolution, used to simplify the input file for speeding up the slicing job and reducing memory usage. High-resolution models often carry more detail than printers can render. Set to zero to disable any simplification and use full resolution from input.
resolution.label: Slice resolution

retract_before_travel.description: Retraction is not triggered when travel moves are shorter than this length.
retract_before_travel.label: Minimum travel after retraction

retract_before_wipe.description: With bowden extruders, it may be wise to do some amount of quick retract before doing the wipe movement.
retract_before_wipe.label: Retract amount before wipe

retract_layer_change.description: This flag enforces a retraction whenever a Z move is done.
retract_layer_change.label: Retract on layer change

retract_length.description: When retraction is triggered, filament is pulled back by the specified amount (the length is measured on raw filament, before it enters the extruder).
retract_length.label: Retraction length

retract_length_toolchange.description: When retraction is triggered before changing tool, filament is pulled back by the specified amount (the length is measured on raw filament, before it enters the extruder).
retract_length_toolchange.label: Length

retract_lift_above.description: If you set this to a positive value, Z lift will only take place above the specified absolute Z. You can tune this setting for skipping lift on the first layers.
retract_lift_above.label: Above Z

retract_lift_below.description: If you set this to a positive value, Z lift will only take place below the specified absolute Z. You can tune this setting for limiting lift to the first layers.
retract_lift_below.label: Below Z

retract_restart_extra.description: When the retraction is compensated after the travel move, the extruder will push this additional amount of filament. This setting is rarely needed.
retract_restart_extra.label: Deretraction extra length

retract_restart_extra_toolchange.description: When the retraction is compensated after changing tool, the extruder will push this additional amount of filament.
retract_restart_extra_toolchange.label: Extra length on restart

retract_speed.description: The speed for retractions (it only applies to the extruder motor).
retract_speed.label: Retraction Speed

single_extruder_multi_material.description: The printer multiplexes filaments into a single hot end.
single_extruder_multi_material.label: Single Extruder Multi Material

single_extruder_multi_material_priming.description: If enabled, all printing extruders will be primed at the front edge of the print bed at the start of the print.
single_extruder_multi_material_priming.label: Prime all printing extruders

skirt_distance.description: Distance between skirt and brim (when draft shield is not used) or objects.
skirt_distance.label: Distance from brim/object

skirt_height.description: Height of skirt expressed in layers.
skirt_height.label: Skirt height

skirts.description: Number of loops for the skirt. If the Minimum Extrusion Length option is set, the number of loops might be greater than the one configured here. Set this to zero to disable skirt completely.
skirts.label: Loops (minimum)

slice_closing_radius.description: Cracks smaller than 2x gap closing radius are being filled during the triangle mesh slicing. The gap closing operation may reduce the final print resolution, therefore it is advisable to keep the value reasonably low.
slice_closing_radius.label: Slice gap closing radius

slicing_mode.description: Use "Even-odd" for 3DLabPrint airplane models. Use "Close holes" to close all holes in the model.
slicing_mode.label: Slicing Mode

slowdown_below_layer_time.description: If layer print time is estimated below this number of seconds, print moves speed will be scaled down to extend duration to this value.
slowdown_below_layer_time.label: Slow down if layer print time is below

small_perimeter_speed.description: This separate setting will affect the speed of perimeters having radius <= 6.5mm (usually holes). If expressed as percentage (for example: 80%) it will be calculated on the perimeters speed setting above. Set to zero for auto.
small_perimeter_speed.label: Small perimeters

solid_infill_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for solid infill. Set zero to use the value for infill.
solid_infill_acceleration.label: Solid infill

solid_infill_below_area.description: Force solid infill for regions having a smaller area than the specified threshold.
solid_infill_below_area.label: Solid infill threshold area

solid_infill_every_layers.description: This feature allows to force a solid layer every given number of layers. Zero to disable. You can set this to any value (for example 9999); Slic3r will automatically choose the maximum possible number of layers to combine according to nozzle diameter and layer height.
solid_infill_every_layers.label: Solid infill every

solid_infill_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing solid infill.
solid_infill_extruder.label: Solid infill extruder

solid_infill_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for infill for solid surfaces. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise 1.125 x nozzle diameter will be used. If expressed as percentage (for example 90%) it will be computed over layer height.
solid_infill_extrusion_width.label: Solid infill

solid_infill_speed.description: Speed for printing solid regions (top/bottom/internal horizontal shells). This can be expressed as a percentage (for example: 80%) over the default infill speed above. Set to zero for auto.
solid_infill_speed.label: Solid infill

solid_layers.description: Number of solid layers to generate on top and bottom surfaces.
solid_layers.label: Solid layers

solid_min_thickness.description: Minimum thickness of a top / bottom shell
solid_min_thickness.label: Minimum thickness of a top / bottom shell

spiral_vase.description: This feature will raise Z gradually while printing a single-walled object in order to remove any visible seam. This option requires a single perimeter, no infill, no top solid layers and no support material. You can still set any number of bottom solid layers as well as skirt/brim loops. It won't work when printing more than one single object.
spiral_vase.label: Spiral vase

staggered_inner_seams.description: This option causes the inner seams to be shifted backwards based on their depth, forming a zigzag pattern.
staggered_inner_seams.label: Staggered inner seams

standby_temperature_delta.description: Temperature difference to be applied when an extruder is not active. The value is not used when 'idle_temperature' in filament settings is defined.
standby_temperature_delta.label: Temperature variation

start_filament_gcode.description: This start procedure is inserted at the beginning, after any printer start gcode (and after any toolchange to this filament in case of multi-material printers). This is used to override settings for a specific filament. If PrusaSlicer detects M104, M109, M140 or M190 in your custom codes, such commands will not be prepended automatically so you're free to customize the order of heating commands and other custom actions. Note that you can use placeholder variables for all PrusaSlicer settings, so you can put a "M109 S[first_layer_temperature]" command wherever you want. If you have multiple extruders, the gcode is processed in extruder order.
start_filament_gcode.label: Start G-code

start_gcode.default_value: G28 ; home all axes\nG1 Z5 F5000 ; lift nozzle\n
start_gcode.description: This start procedure is inserted at the beginning, possibly prepended by temperature-changing commands. See 'autoemit_temperature_commands'.
start_gcode.label: Start G-code

support_material_angle.description: Use this setting to rotate the support material pattern on the horizontal plane.
support_material_angle.label: Pattern angle

support_material_auto.description: If checked, supports will be generated automatically based on the overhang threshold value. If unchecked, supports will be generated inside the "Support Enforcer" volumes only.
support_material_auto.label: Auto generated supports

support_material_bottom_contact_distance.description: The vertical distance between the object top surface and the support material interface. If set to zero, support_material_contact_distance will be used for both top and bottom contact Z distances.
support_material_bottom_contact_distance.label: Bottom contact Z distance

support_material_bottom_interface_layers.description: Number of interface layers to insert between the object(s) and support material. Set to -1 to use support_material_interface_layers
support_material_bottom_interface_layers.label: Bottom interface layers

support_material_buildplate_only.description: Only create support if it lies on a build plate. Don't create support on a print.
support_material_buildplate_only.label: Support on build plate only

support_material_closing_radius.description: For snug supports, the support regions will be merged using morphological closing operation. Gaps smaller than the closing radius will be filled in.
support_material_closing_radius.label: Closing radius

support_material_contact_distance.description: The vertical distance between object and support material interface. Setting this to 0 will also prevent Slic3r from using bridge flow and speed for the first object layer.
support_material_contact_distance.label: Top contact Z distance

support_material_enforce_layers.description: Generate support material for the specified number of layers counting from bottom, regardless of whether normal support material is enabled or not and regardless of any angle threshold. This is useful for getting more adhesion of objects having a very thin or poor footprint on the build plate.
support_material_enforce_layers.label: Enforce support for the first

support_material_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing support material, raft and skirt (1+, 0 to use the current extruder to minimize tool changes).
support_material_extruder.label: Support material/raft/skirt extruder

support_material_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for support material. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise nozzle diameter will be used. If expressed as percentage (for example 90%) it will be computed over layer height.
support_material_extrusion_width.label: Support material

support_material_interface_contact_loops.description: Cover the top contact layer of the supports with loops. Disabled by default.
support_material_interface_contact_loops.label: Interface loops

support_material_interface_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing support material interface (1+, 0 to use the current extruder to minimize tool changes). This affects raft too.
support_material_interface_extruder.label: Support material/raft interface extruder

support_material_interface_layers.description: Number of interface layers to insert between the object(s) and support material.
support_material_interface_layers.label: Top interface layers

support_material_interface_pattern.description: Pattern used to generate support material interface. Default pattern for non-soluble support interface is Rectilinear, while default pattern for soluble support interface is Concentric.
support_material_interface_pattern.label: Interface pattern

support_material_interface_spacing.description: Spacing between interface lines. Set zero to get a solid interface.
support_material_interface_spacing.label: Interface pattern spacing

support_material_interface_speed.description: Speed for printing support material interface layers. If expressed as percentage (for example 50%) it will be calculated over support material speed.
support_material_interface_speed.label: Support material interface

support_material_pattern.description: Pattern used to generate support material.
support_material_pattern.label: Pattern

support_material_style.description: Style and shape of the support towers. Projecting the supports into a regular grid will create more stable supports, while snug support towers will save material and reduce object scarring.
support_material_style.label: Style

support_material_synchronize_layers.description: Synchronize support layers with the object print layers. This is useful with multi-material printers, where the extruder switch is expensive. This option is only available when top contact Z distance is set to zero.
support_material_synchronize_layers.label: Synchronize with object layers

support_material_threshold.description: Support material will not be generated for overhangs whose slope angle (90o = vertical) is above the given threshold. In other words, this value represent the most horizontal slope (measured from the horizontal plane) that you can print without support material. Set to zero for automatic detection (recommended).
support_material_threshold.label: Overhang threshold

support_material_with_sheath.description: Add a sheath (a single perimeter line) around the base support. This makes the support more reliable, but also more difficult to remove.
support_material_with_sheath.label: With sheath around the support

support_material_xy_spacing.description: XY separation between an object and its support. If expressed as percentage (for example 50%), it will be calculated over external perimeter width.
support_material_xy_spacing.label: XY separation between an object and its support

support_tree_angle.description: The maximum angle of the branches, when the branches have to avoid the model. Use a lower angle to make them more vertical and more stable. Use a higher angle to be able to have more reach.
support_tree_angle.label: Maximum Branch Angle

support_tree_angle_slow.description: The preferred angle of the branches, when they do not have to avoid the model. Use a lower angle to make them more vertical and more stable. Use a higher angle for branches to merge faster.
support_tree_angle_slow.label: Preferred Branch Angle

support_tree_branch_diameter.description: The diameter of the thinnest branches of organic support. Thicker branches are more sturdy. Branches towards the base will be thicker than this.
support_tree_branch_diameter.label: Branch Diameter

support_tree_branch_diameter_angle.description: The angle of the branches' diameter as they gradually become thicker towards the bottom. An angle of 0 will cause the branches to have uniform thickness over their length. A bit of an angle can increase stability of the organic support.
support_tree_branch_diameter_angle.label: Branch Diameter Angle

support_tree_branch_diameter_double_wall.description: Branches with area larger than the area of a circle of this diameter will be printed with double walls for stability. Set this value to zero for no double walls.
support_tree_branch_diameter_double_wall.label: Branch Diameter with double walls

support_tree_branch_distance.description: How far apart the branches need to be when they touch the model. Making this distance small will cause the tree support to touch the model at more points, causing better overhang but making support harder to remove.
support_tree_branch_distance.label: Branch Distance

support_tree_tip_diameter.description: Branch tip diameter for organic supports.
support_tree_tip_diameter.label: Tip Diameter

support_tree_top_rate.description: Adjusts the density of the support structure used to generate the tips of the branches. A higher value results in better overhangs but the supports are harder to remove, thus it is recommended to enable top support interfaces instead of a high branch density value if dense interfaces are needed.
support_tree_top_rate.label: Branch Density

temperature.description: Nozzle temperature for layers after the first one. Set this to zero to disable temperature control commands in the output G-code.
temperature.label: Other layers

template_custom_gcode.description: This G-code will be used as a custom code
template_custom_gcode.label: Custom G-code

thick_bridges.description: If enabled, bridges are more reliable, can bridge longer distances, but may look worse. If disabled, bridges look better but are reliable just for shorter bridged distances.
thick_bridges.label: Thick bridges

thin_walls.description: Detect single-width walls (parts where two extrusions don't fit and we need to collapse them into a single trace).
thin_walls.label: Detect thin walls

thumbnails.description:
Picture sizes to be stored into a .gcode / .bgcode and .sl1 / .sl1s files, in the following format: "XxY/EXT, XxY/EXT, ..."
Currently supported extensions are PNG, QOI and JPG.
thumbnails.label: G-code thumbnails

thumbnails_format.description: Format of G-code thumbnails: PNG for best quality, JPG for smallest size, QOI for low memory firmware
thumbnails_format.label: Format of G-code thumbnails

toolchange_gcode.description: This custom code is inserted before every toolchange. Placeholder variables for all PrusaSlicer settings as well as {toolchange_z}, {previous_extruder} and {next_extruder} can be used. When a tool-changing command which changes to the correct extruder is included (such as T{next_extruder}), PrusaSlicer will emit no other such command. It is therefore possible to script custom behaviour both before and after the toolchange.
toolchange_gcode.label: Tool change G-code

top_fill_pattern.description: Fill pattern for top infill. This only affects the top visible layer, and not its adjacent solid shells.
top_fill_pattern.label: Top fill pattern

top_infill_extrusion_width.description: Set this to a non-zero value to set a manual extrusion width for infill for top surfaces. You may want to use thinner extrudates to fill all narrow regions and get a smoother finish. If left zero, default extrusion width will be used if set, otherwise nozzle diameter will be used. If expressed as percentage (for example 90%) it will be computed over layer height.
top_infill_extrusion_width.label: Top solid infill

top_solid_infill_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for top solid infill. Set zero to use the value for solid infill.
top_solid_infill_acceleration.label: Top solid infill

top_solid_infill_speed.description: Speed for printing top solid layers (it only applies to the uppermost external layers and not to their internal solid layers). You may want to slow down this to get a nicer surface finish. This can be expressed as a percentage (for example: 80%) over the solid infill speed above. Set to zero for auto.
top_solid_infill_speed.label: Top solid infill

top_solid_layers.description: Number of solid layers to generate on top surfaces.
top_solid_layers.label: Top

top_solid_min_thickness.description: The number of top solid layers is increased above top_solid_layers if necessary to satisfy minimum thickness of top shell. This is useful to prevent pillowing effect when printing with variable layer height.
top_solid_min_thickness.label: Top

travel_acceleration.description: This is the acceleration your printer will use for travel moves. Set zero to disable acceleration control for travel.
travel_acceleration.label: Travel

travel_lift_before_obstacle.description: If enabled, PrusaSlicer detects obstacles along the travel path and makes the slope steeper in case an obstacle might be hit during the initial phase of the travel.
travel_lift_before_obstacle.label: Steeper ramp before obstacles

travel_max_lift.description: Maximum lift height of the ramping lift. It may not be reached if the next position is close to the old one.
travel_max_lift.label: Maximum ramping lift

travel_ramping_lift.description: Generates a ramping lift instead of lifting the extruder directly upwards. The travel is split into two phases: the ramp and the standard horizontal travel. This option helps reduce stringing.
travel_ramping_lift.label: Use ramping lift

travel_slope.description: Slope of the ramp in the initial phase of the travel.
travel_slope.label: Ramping slope angle

travel_speed.description: Speed for travel moves (jumps between distant extrusion points).
travel_speed.label: Travel

travel_speed_z.description:
Speed for movements along the Z axis.
When set to zero, the value is ignored and regular travel speed is used instead.
travel_speed_z.label: Z travel

use_firmware_retraction.description: This setting uses G10 and G11 commands to have the firmware handle the retraction. Note that this has to be supported by firmware.
use_firmware_retraction.label: Use firmware retraction

use_relative_e_distances.description: If your firmware requires relative E values, check this, otherwise leave it unchecked. Most firmwares use absolute values.
use_relative_e_distances.label: Use relative E distances

use_volumetric_e.description: This experimental setting uses outputs the E values in cubic millimeters instead of linear millimeters. If your firmware doesn't already know filament diameter(s), you can put commands like 'M200 D[filament_diameter_0] T0' in your start G-code in order to turn volumetric mode on and use the filament diameter associated to the filament selected in Slic3r. This is only supported in recent Marlin.
use_volumetric_e.label: Use volumetric E

variable_layer_height.description: Some printers or printer setups may have difficulties printing with a variable layer height. Enabled by default.
variable_layer_height.label: Enable variable layer height feature

wall_distribution_count.description: The number of perimeters, counted from the center, over which the variation needs to be spread. Lower values mean that the outer perimeters don't change in width.
wall_distribution_count.label: Perimeter distribution count

wall_transition_angle.description: When to create transitions between even and odd numbers of perimeters. A wedge shape with an angle greater than this setting will not have transitions and no perimeters will be printed in the center to fill the remaining space. Reducing this setting reduces the number and length of these center perimeters, but may leave gaps or overextrude.
wall_transition_angle.label: Perimeter transitioning threshold angle

wall_transition_filter_deviation.description: Prevent transitioning back and forth between one extra perimeter and one less. This margin extends the range of extrusion widths which follow to [Minimum perimeter width - margin, 2 * Minimum perimeter width + margin]. Increasing this margin reduces the number of transitions, which reduces the number of extrusion starts/stops and travel time. However, large extrusion width variation can lead to under- or overextrusion problems. If expressed as a percentage (for example 25%), it will be computed based on the nozzle diameter.
wall_transition_filter_deviation.label: Perimeter transitioning filter margin

wall_transition_length.description: When transitioning between different numbers of perimeters as the part becomes thinner, a certain amount of space is allotted to split or join the perimeter segments. If expressed as a percentage (for example 100%), it will be computed based on the nozzle diameter.
wall_transition_length.label: Perimeter transition length

wipe.description: This flag will move the nozzle while retracting to minimize the possible blob on leaky extruders.
wipe.label: Wipe while retracting

wipe_into_infill.description: Purging after toolchange will be done inside this object's infills. This lowers the amount of waste but may result in longer print time  due to additional travel moves.
wipe_into_infill.label: Wipe into this object's infill

wipe_into_objects.description: Object will be used to purge the nozzle after a toolchange to save material that would otherwise end up in the wipe tower and decrease print time. Colours of the objects will be mixed as a result.
wipe_into_objects.label: Wipe into this object

wipe_tower.description: Multi material printers may need to prime or purge extruders on tool changes. Extrude the excess material into the wipe tower.
wipe_tower.label: Enable

wipe_tower_bridging.description: Maximal distance between supports on sparse infill sections.
wipe_tower_bridging.label: Maximal bridging distance

wipe_tower_cone_angle.description: Angle at the apex of the cone that is used to stabilize the wipe tower. Larger angle means wider base.
wipe_tower_cone_angle.label: Stabilization cone apex angle

wipe_tower_extra_spacing.description: Spacing of purge lines on the wipe tower.
wipe_tower_extra_spacing.label: Wipe tower purge lines spacing

wipe_tower_extruder.description: The extruder to use when printing perimeter of the wipe tower. Set to 0 to use the one that is available (non-soluble would be preferred).
wipe_tower_extruder.label: Wipe tower extruder

wipe_tower_no_sparse_layers.description: If enabled, the wipe tower will not be printed on layers with no toolchanges. On layers with a toolchange, extruder will travel downward to print the wipe tower. User is responsible for ensuring there is no collision with the print.
wipe_tower_no_sparse_layers.label: No sparse layers (EXPERIMENTAL)

wipe_tower_rotation_angle.description: Wipe tower rotation angle with respect to x-axis.
wipe_tower_rotation_angle.label: Wipe tower rotation angle

wipe_tower_x.description: X coordinate of the left front corner of a wipe tower
wipe_tower_x.label: Position X

wipe_tower_y.description: Y coordinate of the left front corner of a wipe tower
wipe_tower_y.label: Position Y

wiping_volumes_extruders.description: This vector saves required volumes to change from/to each tool used on the wipe tower. These values are used to simplify creation of the full purging volumes below.
wiping_volumes_extruders.label: Purging volumes - load/unload volumes

wiping_volumes_matrix.description: This matrix describes volumes (in cubic milimetres) required to purge the new filament on the wipe tower for any given pair of tools.
wiping_volumes_matrix.label: Purging volumes - matrix

xy_size_compensation.description: The object will be grown/shrunk in the XY plane by the configured value (negative = inwards, positive = outwards). This might be useful for fine-tuning hole sizes.
xy_size_compensation.label: XY Size Compensation

z_offset.description: This value will be added (or subtracted) from all the Z coordinates in the output G-code. It is used to compensate for bad Z endstop position: for example, if your endstop zero actually leaves the nozzle 0.3mm far from the print bed, set this to -0.3 (or fix your endstop).
z_offset.label: Z offset
